{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/using-the-chi-squared-test-for-feature-selection-with-implementation-b15a4dad93f1", "time": 1683016387.8715708, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/using-the-chi-squared-test-for-feature-selection-with-implementation-b15a4dad93f1/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Using the Chi-Squared test for feature selection with implementation | by Dr. Saptarsi Goswami | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Using the Chi-Squared test for feature selection with implementation", "description": "Let\u2019s approach this problem of feature selection using Chi-Square a question and answer style. If you are a video guy, you may check out our youtube lecture on the same. For any ML or DL problem, the\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://youtu.be/hkDfi5j-6lM", "anchor_text": "same", "paragraph_index": 0}], "all_paragraphs": ["Let\u2019s approach this problem of feature selection using Chi-Square a question and answer style. If you are a video guy, you may check out our youtube lecture on the same.", "Question 1: What is a feature?", "For any ML or DL problem, the data is arranged in rows and columns. Let\u2019s take the example of a titanic shipwreck problem.", "Question 2: What are the different types of features?", "Without getting into too many details, let\u2019s follow the above example:", "Question 3: What is feature selection?", "In the titanic shipwreck dataset, the problem to solve is given the characteristics of passengers, it is to be determined whether the passenger survived or not ( i.e. whether he got access to a boat or not). So, this is a classification problem.", "If the original dataset we have 8 features about the passenger and a classification model brings about 90% classification accuracy, the objective of feature selection is to select maybe 3 or 4 out of the 8 and still achieve similar accuracy.", "With a smaller number of features:", "Question 5: What is the connection of feature selection with chi-square?", "Actually, it\u2019s not about chi -Squared rather it\u2019s about hypothesis testing. A typical setup for the same is:", "It may be noted, these techniques are called univariate techniques as we inspect each feature separately.", "Chi-Square is to be used when the feature is categorical, the target variable is any way can be thought as categorical. It measures the degree of association between two categorical variables. If both are numeric, we can use Pearson\u2019s product-moment correlation, and if the attribute is numerical and there are two classes we can use a t-test if more than two classes we can use ANOVA", "We can start with a simple visualization when we approach the effect of Sex on survival status.", "The above visualization clearly tells, that ratio of males is to females is not the same across the two classes. Hypothesis testing is a more formal way of doing the same. The Chi-Squared statistics are calculated using the following formula where \u201cO\u201d stands for observed or actual and \u201cE\u201d stands for expected value if these two categories are independent. If they are independent these O and E values will be close and if they have some association then the Chi-squared value will be high.", "The above table shows Sex vs survival status of the passengers. This is also called the contingency table.", "These Chi-Square statistics are adjusted by the degree of freedom which varies with the number of levels the variable has got and the number of levels the class variable has got.", "It may be noted Chi-Square can be used for the numerical variable as well after it is suitably discretized.", "Question 6: How to implement the same?", "We are going to do feature selection on the wine dataset", "Let\u2019s look at the chi-square scores", "It will print the values as follows", "Now, if we want to select the top four features, we can do simply the following", "Chi-Square is a very simple tool for univariate feature selection for classification. It does no